< Review>
Great park! Beautiful grass. Dog fun zone is bark dust but larger than Crystal Cove and Heritage Park dog areas.
Lovely area with picnic tables and a playground.
Individual outdoor restroom stalls with outdoor hand washing station with soap and paper towels.
Not very busy on weekdays usually, as you can see from the photos.
Plenty of free street parking.<//Review>

< Text>
We went to the park to use the enclosed dog park. It's a great facility to play catch(sic) with you're furry friend. There are several water bowls and water stations at the enclosure and doggie bags. The #1 reason for the 2 Stars is that it is mostly dirt or powdered wood chips (70%), as they have not replenished or refreshed the wood chips in quite some time. There is never anybody else using the dog park, probably due to the dirt. If you dont mind having to give your dog a bath afterwards its 5 Stars.<//Text>

< Text>
Phlight had a great atmosphere and the food was delicious! Nice place to have a light dinner and a glass of wine with friends or significant other.  I recommend the Bacon wrapped dates (amazing!) and the cheese platter. I also had a phlight of wine. They give you 3 to 6 3oz servings. Great way to try out the different wines they serve. Oh, let me not forget, the Pork Belly tacos.... wow! Must try!<//Text>

</record></dataset><record>
<Rate>5< /Rate><gmapID>0x80c2d3ec09b6d157:0xfa02870e3ae9953<//gmapID><Text>very delicious nice workers< /Text><pictures>None<//pictures><date>1550860016447</date><resp>None</resp>< user>
100867608177739161247</user>
< Name>
Johnnie Zamora<//Name>
</record></dataset><record>
<response>None</response><Time>1479669485220</Time><Pictures>None< /Pictures><Rating>5<//Rating><GmapID>0x80c2d3ec09b6d157:0xfa02870e3ae9953< /GmapID><Review>This was my first time coming coming to super to this restaurant. I had read the reviews, both positive and not positive, yet I came with an open mind.

Let's start with the menu. The menu has a very simple and pragmatic approach to fine cuisine. The menu doesn't overwhelm you with complex combo platters like Chilis, BJ's, the YardHouse or the Olive Garden. More than often these large national restaurant chains try to fill you up with the main course item, complimented with a "side of something". Often the side of something is rice, potatoes or some sort of carb based food item to fill you. Phlights menu is a very a la carte offering; you order exactly what you see and will have made fresh to order.

The menu has a nice well rounded assortment of seafood, steaks and chicken. The wine list was neatly organized too. There was California wines and Spanish wines as well.

Service. My wife and I opted for counter top service on the bar. The server was friendly, knowledgeable and attentive. He took our order, and brought our meals in stages. Service was impeccable. We gave the server a 10.

Cooking and preparation. As we sat on the counter top area,we could see our ala carte meals being prepared. Every meal was prepared exactly how I liked my food. Our meals were not massed prepared with other customers orders.

Our order: Diablo Spicey Shrimp, Empanadas, Flank Steak and parsley yellow rice.I spend 2-3 months in Europe every year and I'll spend a few days in Spain. All the meals had the look and taste of Spanish Mediterranean cuisine that I had previously enjoyed in times before. The meals were absolutely delicious. The shrimp could have used a pinch of salt and fresh roasted garlic, but that is more of my personal taste.

Environment. The setting is perfect. It's nice and classy with a large open room of tables that neatly are aligned in such a way were you and your guests are able to enjoy super and friendly conversations without the people sitting next not eavesdropping. So there is a sense of privacy.  Another big plus is this restaurant is not loud with blaring TV'splaying sporting events, where the TV is so loud that you have to speak over the TV volume.

If you are looking for quiet and romantic setting for two or small group gathering getting together for a night out or special occasion - this is the place.

Phlight restaurant has Spanish Mediterranean look and feel with meals that will compliment the setting.

When you walk out of Phlight - I guarantee you you would have enjoyed a memorable experience.

Mario Gastelum< /Review><user_id>100138550394205317739<//user_id>< name>
Mario Gastelum<//name>
</record>
</dataset><record>
<review>First time here found it on Yelp place was outstanding delicious food good service definitely going to come back here<//review><username>Andrew Guerrero<//username>< gmapID>

</dataset><record>
< review>
Came here with my best friend and the ambience was lovely, the service was very friendly and alert, but the food was okay. It was a new place we wanted to try out so we ordered the Brussel sprouts, the ahi tuna tostada, and the lengua tacos. We wanted to order a couple more things, but they were 86'd, we didn't mind. They only had enough lengua for one taco, so half an order, so we asked if we could do one lengua and one pork belly. The lengua taco was on point, it was so well cooked and flavored that I would go back just for that.  The pork belly, not so much. It had a mild flavor and it was too charred for my taste. The sauces that came with both tacos were delicious and paired well with the tacos. The roasted brussel sprouts came next,  the flavor of the dish was very cohesive and flavorful, but it got boring halfway through and the balsamic sauce became too powerful. The ahi tuna tostada was a big disappointment. The tuna was finely minced, or grinded, but there was not much flavorful except for the pico.

We finished our shared dishes and moved onto dessert. We had the chocolate souffl√© and the banana pudding. The souffl√© was lackluster, it didn't scream this was well executed. The bread pudding as well, the ice cream they used for both plates were delicious, only because they were Tillamook ice cream.

I won't write off this place just yet, will come back and I feel like they will change my opinion.< /review>

<Time>1595624494718<//Time>< Name>
John P<//Name>
<Resp>None</Resp>< userid>
116363788318643010750< /userid>
<Rating>5</Rating><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM0cjkohdAwEtjMwibC7oe9NvEFbPi4ZFOK2XvR=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPpOi3LWcWqJ_gGaZd3bjTL8jilnMn_3prw521K=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOfsK4zA5z03NR7BDAWnm3DpBzx6KldOvGoxEIe=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP6A7LSCqzOxComYgnRzYf_GRjV9_I1fcf7Qg3H=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP2xisEomCP-yzj-KDmQIstqVPV76Jk5zOJBZOS=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNBHJAH-4gEVDiWv_q6MHFGd7HICNGBvbhhvs7a=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pictures>< text>
Source tufa area is a federal property. It is free for the holder of the U.S. National Park Annual Pass, otherwise you pay $3 per adult. It is free for children under 16. There are national park rangers patrolling the area.

This vista point is located south of the Mono Lake. If you drive from yosemite park, turn right on hwy 390 at Tioga pass for couple of miles, then make a left turn on 120 East for another mile or two, make a left turn again on Test Station road. There is a half mile unpaved road that will finally lead you to the parking lot.  As many folks pointed out, there is constant traffic enforcement on highway 395, the car before us was moving at 80 miles per hour and got a ticket, it looks like a speed trap to me. Just drive slowly!

This place is one of the most famous photography spots near Yosemite Nation Park. We arrived in the afternoon, which is not usually a good time for taking pictures. But there was a summer thunder storm around the lake. Park ranger told us it is rare to have thunder storm at this time of the year. In July, the temperature can easily go to upper 90 Fahr. But we are lucky, the weather is cool, and scattered rains drove away the flies and the water did not smell as said by others.

Do not climb the Tufa tower, I happened to see a park ranger warned a couple who climbed to the Tufa Tower for a better selfie, bad idea.
Due to Covid-19,  there are no more naturalist guided canoe tour this summer.< /text>

It's not very common to get exceptional service these days. A lot of employees are not taken care of very well so that shows when it is time to provide service to the client. But when it does happen it is more than just a little noticeable . It is truly amazing. That is what my experience was like with Brandon Anderson he was courteous but firm when he told me what the policies were. However I needed a special exception and it was declined by Management. I tried to solve the issue on my own but it was more than I could handle you see because I am disabled. When I came back to Brandon he went the extra mile for me and I am so impressed with his people skills. He made it important to help an old man who needed help.  Unfortunately most people wouldn't take the time. He told me in eleven years he had not had to do what I needed. Even with the task of managing his regular task he went out of his way to help me and I will be forever grateful.

This man is a true "Champion" . Brandon Thank you so much. I appreciate you going the extra mile and I want everyone to know the kind of person you are. They say Character is the person you are when nobody is looking. I am sure your Parent's would be proud to know the Man you have become.

God Bless you Thank you for going the extra mile for me

Regards

<date>1545751324498< /date>< rating>

< Review>
Great, old fashioned friendly service. Good supply of equipment for a group of half a dozen for beginner ski rentals, including jackets and pants.

One thing to mention is that while the woman behind the counter is helpful, as other reviewers have written she can come across a bit condescending. I was fine, especially since I tended to agree with her useful advice for managing a group of first time skiers and ensuring they were well protected and warm, but if you have thin skin you may not find it tolerable. She should work on her communication style. Making the customer feel stupid, especially tourists likely to write a 1 star review after having their egos bruised, is generally not a good thing for your business.

That said, thank you to all the owners and staff for taking care of us all on our Christmas vacation. A warm Merry Christmas to you all.</Review>

<pics>None</pics><name>Tyler Fremming< /name>< Rate>
5</Rate>
< Date>
1470845695740</Date>
<text>Solid small business that has been holding down the fort for Arnold & Bear Valley in terms of sporting goods for a long time.

They have a knack carrying those items you seem to have forgotten, which makes them indispensable. Also, while their prices are not going to beat walmart/amazon etc., they are fair priced for a small shop up the hill, and you will save greatly in lieu of high ski resort prices

My family built cabin in Arnold since '69.  Many businesses have come and gone with good and bad snow years, and recession.  This business has been here for close to 20 years I believe,  they do a great job for their size.  They always help with whatever they can.  This includes  walking in for fishing advice, even if you didn't need to purchase anything.

A great small business I recommend patronizing if you have the opportunity.</text>< user>

I went here for the first time on 12/21/18 and the young lady helping me was super rude. The place had 2 patrons sitting and eating and I felt like the lady was rushing me to hurry up and pick the scoops of meat, sauces, etc. There was no one behind me and I even stated ‚Äúsorry it‚Äôs my first time here‚Äù. She didn‚Äôt once smile at me which should‚Äôve been the first sign of disappointment. Lucky there was another young man working who was much nicer when checking me out. He smiled, thanked me and had a much better attitude than the young lady that looked as though she‚Äôd rather get hit by a car than help me. I felt the prices were a little steep, but I love and was craving poki. I took my meal to go, and the second I headed toward the door the young lady started chatting it up with the young man, laughing and seemingly much better than she was moments before when serving me. (so rude!) nonetheless I figured maybe she had been working all day or had a rough day or something so I tried to chalk it up to nothing. But when I went home the poki bowl was just ok. The sauces weren‚Äôt really adding to the dish and I‚Äôve had much tastier poki elsewhere. I won‚Äôt be back, sadly. I was let down and would much rather take my business to Poki N Salad. Their poki is delicious, fresh, their sauces are super flavorful, they have larger servings with a cheaper price, AND the employees smile and are nice to you when ordering.< /text>

The quality of goods is easily it's main draw. After that, it's downhill. Often you are charged more than the signage dictates. < Rate>
1</Rate>
< text>
This is a critique of the donation station:
Just tried to donate a rug to Goodwill. It has no stains and came from a house with no animals, no smoking, wood flooring (the pictures show carpeting under the rug, I took these photos when I arrived at another house, perturbed that I still had it), and a very low traffic room. I have been to this location numerous times to donate items that are still in good condition with no stains or tears and have been turned away because it would not blend in with the other items on the sales floor. I have finally learned my lesson and have decided to stop wasting my time sorting between items that have tears and/or stains and items that do not. I am going to throw everything away. When I return home, I will be cutting the rug up and dumping it in my trash to be picked up on Tuesday morning.

Fifteen years ago this store accepted anything that was still in sale condition, now they pick and choose depending on how it will look in their store. I guess donating to Goodwill is not for me. I am saying good riddance to donating and hello to land fills. (Do not suggest the two others in walking distance of my house, they are even more critical of donations).

The attached photos have horrendous lighting (They were deleted the first time I tried to post them, if they are not attached, it's because they were deleted again in the upload process). The rug has two shades of green, two shades of brown, and one cream, and one grey.</text>

<Text>6/6/13

ONE DOLLA MAKES ME HOLLA

Whether or not the higher-ups of this not-for-profit business are making a lot of money, I support Goodwill because 1) I like discounted items, 2) its important to reuse, 3) the company hires people who may otherwise face challenges with employment.

This Goodwill in particular can be disorganized at times, mostly due to its rather large size. For the most part, houseware and clothing are kept separate, so I can't complain if slacks are mixed in with jeans. I'm more likely to shop for clothes in Walnut Creek or Danville thrift stores anyhow, unless I'm looking for new Burning Man outfits; but those usually find me without much searching.

On that note, I've scored some amazing and fun pieces of desert clothing in this store. And I have fun walking around it, even when I leave empty-handed.<//Text><name>Amy Palmer<//name><resp>None< /resp><Rating>3< /Rating>< Pics>

< Review>
My elderly mom is a resident in Palm Desert and recently widowed. She has had a service agreement in place with Hyde for her HVAC system for the past several years. During that time, they have done a great job to keep her ancient HVAC system working properly. < text>
After purchasing a home in Palm Springs, we called Hyde's for maintenance of the AC system, which the company had installed about 2 1/2 years ago.  The $149 a year maintenance package seemed reasonable to me, and it was a simple process to set up an appointment.  The lady who helped me on the phone was very friendly and knowledgeable.  Then the appointment arrived, and Casey was early and ready to go on a hot afternoon.  He navigated the floor and room renovations that a were going on in the house, working around the crew with ease.  From first conversation with him, I knew we were in good hands.  Casey took his time , changed out filters, checked ducts, and drainage pipes, all the while explaining things to me in easy-to-understand terms.  We also asked about options to help distribute the air more evenly throughout the house, and he explained considerations in clear, honest communication.  I like that he detailed the benefits of each option.  Anyway, we decided to go with zone cooling but decided a few days later to cancel because we entered a solar panel agreement with a company that we had been considering for quite some time.  Then the more we thought about it, we think a mini-split would serve our purposes better, and we can find one much cheaper.  (The desert experience is all new to us. ..so our heads have been "swimming" with options.)  Anyway, the Hyde's representative was nice and very understanding when I called to cancel.  (By the way, they wanted $500 for move three ducts, and I ended up getting a handyman to do it for $90.)  I will stick with them for the maintenance but will continue to explore other options.  Very nice people all the way around!<//text>

The technician was on time and seemed pleasant. I liked the detail of wearing protective paper booties over his shoes. At first, I thought it was nice that he asked for a broom to clean up the mess of lint and dust he made in my hallway although perhaps that's something he should carry with him. It took me awhile to find my dustpan and broom and when I finally did he'd already picked it up by hand and tossed it on my front patio. That was weird and unprofessional. He could have asked to throw it in the trash. I had to pick it up from my patio.

As for the work, it was a summer service only. He said everything checked out good except we were low on freon which meant we have a leak. He said we need to pay for a $385 leak check. That's a bit expensive so we said we'd reach out to our home warranty insurance company. He said ok and that the leak was all that needed to be done. Once he left and provided the inspection report, we saw it says there is something called a superheat which came up as "Red- requires attention/failed". I don't know what this is and if it's a problem. The word failed insinuates a problem, but because he didn't mention it I just don't know.

Overall, we joined their maintenance plan today with this service and I'm thinking maybe it wasn't a good idea. We will see.

Well fast forward to May 21st and my warranty company inspected my unit and says there is no sign of a leak, freon levels are normal and unit is functioning well. That was an unnecessary $80 copay but at least I didn't pay Hyde's $385. Not happy. Will cancel service plan after fall inspection.

Nov 16. Just had fall inspection.  Technician was nice.  Good experience.  Happy with service today.  I've increased my stars to 3 based on today's experience.  I like having someone come out and service the equipment but the first technician in the spring kind of put me off.< /Review>

< time>

<rate>2<//rate><user_name>Ron Fitzpatrick<//user_name><GmapID>0x80dafbeb644242cd:0xd3a7f71b45fcdc4< /GmapID>< Response>

< user_id>
101504002808100852862<//user_id>
<pics>None<//pics>< review>
Pleasant, cordial, and professional telephone etiquette when making appointments, and when providing reminders, etc. Technicians also are very professional and courteous and "seemingly" efficient while servicing our A/C  System(s). The score I am submitting has more to do with my questioning the competence, professionalism, and followup as related to my recent experience with this company which until now I considered reliable and responsible.

After Hydes' bi-annual servicing per our contract agreement, I reported a "new noise" very audible around one of the return air ducts.  Hydes was informed of the issue and advised that the return appointment would be for late afternoon the following day. A different technician arrived, and agreed that there was an unusual "whining" noise. The technician's explanation was that the newly installed  filter as part of the servicing, was creating a "metallic" interaction with the metal grill; that this can be a normal occurrence, is not that unusual; and that he would return the next day to install an "adhesive" border/band around the opening which is the normal procedure and which would solve the problem.

The technician did not return the following day so growing a little "tired" of hearing this whining throughout the day, I decided to simply replace the filter with one of my own. The noise immediately went away.  While replacing the filter however, I discovered that rather than insert the filter in the recessed part of the grill designed for that purpose,  the filter was forced in above the recess into the larger actual duct opening.  Pieces of rubber/foam wedges (apparently pieces of rubberized piping insulation) had been placed around the edges of the filter to make it fit the opening, the result of which was a more pronounced continuation of the whining noise we were experiencing. This was the approach of the second Hydes technician in an attempt to quell the noise.

Even I am aware that the recess is designed to fit the exact size of the intended filter and does not require rubber wedges,  nor does it require an advanced degree to see or at least figure out the obvious. Quite baffling to say the least, not to mention my disappointment at the lack of efficiency and heretofore perceived competence of Hydes' technical staff.

Hydes otherwise has been quite prompt, courteous and professional in their demeanor.  I am just not sure why this happened particularly while performing such a basic procedure as changing out filters.  Two days later and no word from Hydes.  The technician still has not returned nor bothered to make contact to explain why, apologize, or to reschedule.

After several years of annual service contracts with Hydes, should I now be forced to lower my expectations or just not renew what I thought was a "professional services" contractual arrangement?<//review>
</record></dataset><record>

<Date>1591835981059< /Date><name>Mark Verre< /name><Text>- Hyde's Air Conditioning. 01/03/2020

Simply the Best !

The 2nd of our bi-annual service check up went without a hitch. Not only great peace-of-mind, but extends my warranty. Paying monthly locks me in from any future price increases too.

May, 2018

Top-of-the-line HVAC for the price of a basic level

As our desert temperatures rise now in May, I am so grateful we addressed our HVAC problems in February.

While I can agree with others who have said any brand of HVAC equipment properly installed and maintained will provide excellent service.  My research proved, however, there is a difference ‚Ä¶

Comparing cost, unit efficiency, and features, here is my story.

A $2,700 estimate to repair my existing system seemed like a bad investment as so far, the 7-year old 13-seer system has  required $900 in repairs and replacement parts.  The furnace has been trouble-free despite its 22 year age.   To that end, I solicited prices on an entire HVAC system, Furnace and A/C with equipment from American Standard, Carrier, Lennox and York from several desert vendors, including one displaying at our area membership warehouse.  All were first class in their representation of their products, but one company and one vendor stood out.

HYDES and AMERICAN STANDARD

For the price of a low-end Lennox system via Costco, I was able to acquire a HIGH-END, HIGH-EFFECIENCY model superior to anything the others provide.

Although American Standard is commonly associated with bathroom fittings, a corporate break-up in 2007 resulted in the selling of their plumbing division and a corporate name change to TRANE, who produce HVAC systems under both Trane and American Standard.  You may also be familiar with their parent company Ingersoll-Rand.

American Standard ‚Äì better warranty 12 year compressor

HYDES provides Parts AND Labor for 10 YEARS with their bi-annual maintenance contract.  A typical 2 hour service call would far exceed the maintenance subscription.

On offer was a Zero percent financing option for 36 months making this deal extremely attractive.

Unbelievably QUIET with variable speed compressor, variable speed outdoor condenser fan and variable speed indoor blower.  Talk about COMFORT !

Some local firms have Climate System Representatives who are sales people that evaluate and provide estimates.  HYDES sends out a technician and follow up is provided by company owner, Mike Hyde, who along with his brothers  operate an extremely well-run family organization providing 5-Star Customer Service.  Not surprising that so many of their employees have worked there for years.

A MILLION THANKS, MIKE and to ALL THE CREW AT HYDES.< /Text>< Rating>
5< /Rating>

<Text>The technician was prompt and got to work checking out the A/C system to make sure it was working correctly and to determine if there were any potential problems.  He was thorough  and experienced.  After his lengthy maintenance check, all of the system were working properly.  He explained what he did, such as checking the system for leaks, etc and everything was great.  A couple years ago, the A/C went out in the summer.  Needed someone quick because of my tropical fish, so I picked Hyde from the internet.  That serviceman came within a couple hours and fixed the burned out condenser or capacitor or whatever.  Been working like a charm ever since.  So I chose Hyde to do anymore work if needed.  About a year ago, I had a problem with the A/C.  Apparently the builder put in a 10" intake ducting.  It eventually collapsed.  Hyde came out and found that the builders from Lennar put in the wrong size intake duct.  Should have been 12" diameter.  Hyde came out and replaced it with the proper size.  It was a big, heavy, insulated and awkward piece to drag up into the attic but the technicians did it and solved that problem.  But too bad the warranty ran out from Lennar but it was worth the cost to have it done right.  Got a heating/AC problem.  Call Hyde.<//Text>< Pictures>

<time>1531787719411</time><pics>None</pics>< review>
It was 109 degrees outside yesterday when our A/C stopped working. In a panic, we called Hydes A/C and spoke with a cheerful CSR named Janelle. She quickly set up an inspection & within 2 hours a really nice tech named Jeff Sproul showed up at our door eager to help. Fearful of having to come up with the cash to afford a brand new A/C unit, Jeff quickly diagnosed our problem - just a broken fan motor. The news got even better when he said he had a new one in his truck. Bam, done deal! Within 30 minutes, he had that baby installed and the cool air was flowing! At the time, the temp inside our home was 86 and rising, so their quick, efficient service  literally saved our lives!  Thank you Hydes for exceeding all our expectations!
Stay Blest (Blessed + Best),
Lee K.
